   <titles>
      <title>0-Dimensional Orientation</title>
   </titles>
   <body>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>We may regard a point <math>
                     <latex>P</latex>
                  </math> as a copy of <math>
                     <latex>\RNr[0]</latex>
                  </math>. An orientation on <math>
                     <latex>P</latex>
                  </math> has no intuitive content. It is given by formally assigning the value <math>
                     <latex>+1</latex>
                  </math> or <math>
                     <latex>-1</latex>
                  </math> to <math>
                     <latex>P</latex>
                  </math>.</para.body>
            </para>
            <table align="center" border="3" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="3">
               <row>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>
                           <media type="image" active="0" inline="0">
                              <img src="ims/BlueDot.gif"/>
                           </media>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>positive orientation</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>
                           <math>
                              <latex>\omega(P)=+1</latex>
                           </math>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
               </row>
               <row>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>
                           <media type="image" active="0" inline="0">
                              <img src="ims/RedDot.gif"/>
                           </media>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>negative orientation</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>
                           <math>
                              <latex>\omega(P)=-1</latex>
                           </math>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
               </row>
            </table>
         </block.body>
      </block>
      <block>
         <block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>While the notion of orientation of a point might seem a bit artificial, it is still quite useful. For example in calculus: pick numbers <math>
                     <latex> a&lt;b </latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>\RNr</latex>
                  </math>, and assign orientations as follows:</para.body>
            </para>
            <table align="center" border="3" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="2">
               <row>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>To the interval <math>
                              <latex>[a,b]</latex>
                           </math>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Positive orientation</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
               </row>
               <row>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>To the boundary point <math>
                              <latex>a</latex>
                           </math>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Negative orientation</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
               </row>
               <row>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>To the boundary point <math>
                              <latex>b</latex>
                           </math>
                        </para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
                  <cell>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Positive orientation</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </cell>
               </row>
            </table>
            <para>
               <para.body>Then the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus for a function <math>
                     <latex>f\from [a,b]\to \RNr</latex>
                  </math> with antiderivative <math>
                     <latex>F</latex>
                  </math> may be formulated as follows</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>
					
\aligned
\int_{a}^{b} f(x)\, dx\ &amp;=\ F(b) - F(a) \\
	&amp;=\ \omega(b)F(b) + \omega(a)F(a)
\endaligned

				</latex>
            </math.display>
            <para>
               <para.body>This means that the integral is a quantity which is sensitive to orientation, an observation which is a prerequisite for a full understanding of Stokes Theorem; i.e. the extension of the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus to higher dimensions.</para.body>
            </para>
         </block.body>
      </block>
   </body>
